# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sea-trial
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Variations of gray or grey include achromatic grayscale shades, which lie exactly between white and black, and nearby colors with low colorfulness.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] A selection of a number of these various colors is shown below.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Below is a chart showing the computer web color grays.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] An *achromatic gray* is a gray color in which the values for the red, green and blue components are exactly equal.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] A *chromatic gray* is a color in which one or more of the ratios between red, green and blue is unequal, but only slightly, which is what makes it a shade of gray.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Among the web colors, *gray*, *light gray*, *dark gray*, *dim gray* and *gainsboro* are all achromatic or "neutral" grays, whereas *slate gray*, *light slate gray* and *dark slate gray* are chromatic.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] When the imbalance of the three color ratios in a chromatic gray favors green or blue it is called a "cool" gray, and when it favors red it is called a "warm" gray; all of the web colors' chromatic grays are of the "cool" variety.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The colors white and black are not usually thought of as shades of gray, but they can be thought of as shades of achromatic gray, as both contain equal amounts of red, blue and green.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] White is at the extreme upper end of the achromatic value scale and black is at the extreme lower end of the achromatic value scale, with all the colors normally considered tones of achromatic gray colors in between.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Since achromatic colors have no hue, the hue code (h code) is left blank for achromatic colors (usually marked as a dash).
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Achromatic grays are colors in which the RGB (red, green, and blue) values are exactly equal.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Since achromatic grays have no hue, the hue code (the h in the hsv values of the color) is indicated with a dash.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Achromatic grays are the axis of the color sphere, with white at the north pole and black at the south pole of the color sphere.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The various tones of achromatic gray are along the axis of the color sphere from white at the top of the axis to black at the bottom of the axis.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The first recorded use of **gray** as a color name in the English language was in 700.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] This tone of gray (HTML gray) is universally used as the standard for gray because it is that tone of gray which is halfway between white and black.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Prior to standardization as a web color, *Gainsboro* was included as one of the X11 color names.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] It was, however, absent from the original 1987 version of the list, but present in Paul Raveling's version which added, amongst other things, "[l]ight and off-white colors, copied from several Sinclair Paints color samples".
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] This color is a representation of the color of the metal silver.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] This is supposed to be a metallic color; however, there is no mechanism for displaying metallic colors on a flat computer screen.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] At right is displayed the color *medium gray*, or *gray* in the X11 color names, which is lighter than the HTML/CSS gray shown below.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The coordinates in the X11 were set at 190 to avoid gray being displayed as white on 2-bit grayscale displays.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] See the chart Color names that clash between X11 and HTML/CSS in the X11 color names article to see those colors which are different in HTML/CSS and X11.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Off-grays are colors that are very close to achromatic grays, but whose red, green, and blue color codes are not exactly equal.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Displayed in the adjacent image is the color *ash gray*.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The color **ash gray** is a representation of the color of ash; also known (from its name in Latin language) as cinereous.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The first recorded use of *ash gray* as a color name in English was in 1374.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The color *battleship gray* is displayed in the adjacent image.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] It is so called because the color is the shade of gray from the specular micaceous hematite paint used for rustproofing iron and steel battleships.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The normalized color coordinates for battleship gray are identical to old silver, first recorded as a color name in English in 1905.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The first recorded use of *charcoal* as a color name in English was in 1606.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The first recorded use of *platinum* as a color name in English was in 1918.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Displayed adjacent is the color **taupe gray**.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Displayed in the adjacent image is the color **xanadu**.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The color "xanadu" is a greenish-gray color whose name is derived from the Philodendron.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The color ultimately comes from the 2001 Resene RGB Values List.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Cool grays have noticeably bluish, greenish, or violetish hues.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The first recorded use of *cadet* as a color name in English was in 1915.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Before 1912, the word *cadet gray* was used as a name for a type of military issue uniforms.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Most famously, it was the color of the uniforms of the Confederate Army.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] In 1815, it had earlier become the color of the uniforms of the United States Military Academy (West Point).
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] This color is a dull shade of *blue-gray*.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] This color is identical with color sample No.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] 203 (identified as *gray blue*) at the following website: http://tx4.us/nbs/nbs-g.htm—The ISCC-NBS Dictionary of Colo(u)r Names (1955), a website for stamp collectors to evaluate the colors of their stamps.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Poet George Sterling once wrote a poem calling San Francisco the "cool grey city of love" The phrase *cool grey* as applied to San Francisco refers to the frequent fogs from the Pacific Ocean that envelop the city.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The first recorded use of *slate gray* as a color name in English was in 1705.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The first recorded use of *cinereous* as a color name in English was in 1661.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] This is a warm gray that combines beige and gray.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Its name is believed to have originated from the French word "gris," meaning gray.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] Georgio Armani pioneered its use in fashion in 1975.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] There is a grayish tone of rose called *rose quartz*.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The first recorded use of *rose quartz* as a color name in English was in 1926.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The color displayed at right matches the color sample called *taupe* referenced below in the 1930 book *A Dictionary of Color*, the world standard for color terms before the invention of computers.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] However, the word *taupe* may often be used to refer to lighter shades of taupe today, and therefore another name for this color is *dark taupe*.
[src:sea-trial/battleship-grey] The first use of *taupe* as a color name in English was in the early 19th century.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Belle-Île formed a canton until 2015 when it was merged into the canton of Quiberon as part of a general overhaul.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] The island measures 17 by 9 kilometres (10+1⁄2 by 5+1⁄2 miles) and has an average elevation of 40 metres (130 feet).
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] The coasts are a mixture between dangerously sharp cliff edges on the southwest side, the *Côte Sauvage* ("wild coast"), and placid beaches, the largest being *les Grands Sables* ("the great sands") and navigable harbours on the northeast side.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] The island's climate is oceanic, having less rain and milder winters than on the mainland.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] The two main ports are Le Palais (accessible by ferry from Quiberon, Port-Navalo and Vannes) and Sauzon (accessible by ferry from Quiberon and Lorient).
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] There used to be forests on the island, but these have long disappeared due to increasing agricultural use of the land.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Belle Île experiences a warm-summer Mediterranean climate.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] At the 2009 census, the population of Belle Île was 4,920.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] However, in summer the population may increase to 25,000, with a peak at 35,000 between 15 July and 15 August due to tourist activity.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Belle Île was separated from the mainland about 6000 BC, earlier than the neighbouring islands of Houat and Hœdic.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Archaeological finds from the Bronze Age suggest that the island enjoyed a large increase in population in this time, probably due to improvements in seafaring.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] It was then a naval base for the Veneti.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] The Roman name of the island seems to have been *Vindilis*, which in the Middle Ages became corrupted to *Guedel*.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] During the ninth century Belle-Île belonged to the county of Cornouaille.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] In 1572, the monks of the abbey of Ste Croix at Quimperlé ceded the island to the Retz family, in whose favour it was raised to a marquisate in the following year.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] It subsequently came into the hands of the family of Fouquet.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] The island's fortifications were erected by Vauban on behalf of Nicolas Fouquet, prior to Fouquet incurring the displeasure of Louis XIV; the land was ceded to the crown in 1718.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] The island was held by British troops from 1761, following its capture by an expedition sent out from England, to 1763, when it was returned to France in exchange for Menorca as part of the Peace of Paris.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Because of the upheaval from the conflict, half the population had moved back to the mainland and the abandoned lands were offered to the deported Acadians who settled here in 1766.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] The attacks on Belle Île and siege of Belle Île have been described by Olaudah Equiano (c.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] 1797) in his autobiography, *The Interesting Narrative of the Life of Olaudah Equiano, Or Gustavus Vassa, The African*, 1789, June 1792.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] His book was a bestseller in his own time.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] He became a central figure in the British abolitionist movement, as a forceful abolitionist lecturer, based on his own experiences as a former slave.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Equiano gave a detailed eyewitness report of the attacks and siege.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Much of the island's current population is descended from repatriated Acadian colonists who returned to France after being expelled from Acadia (1755–1764) during the Expulsion of the Acadians.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Today, Belle-Île's population is about 5,300, and its economy is largely dependent on tourism and fishing.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] During the summer the island's population increases dramatically, as many people own a second home on the island due to its secluded location and beaches.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] The island has been a popular location for artists.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Octave Penguilly L'Haridon's 1859 painting *Les Petites mouettes* ("Little Gulls") (1858, Musée des Beaux-Arts de Rennes) depicts the island.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Monet's series of paintings of the rocks at Belle Île astounded the Paris art world when he first exhibited them in 1887.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Most notable are the *Storm, Coast at Belle-Ile* and *Cliffs at Belle-Ile* both rendered in 1886.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Australian born artist John Russell was a man of means and after his marriage to an Italian woman, Mariana Antoinetta Matiocco, he settled at Belle Île off the coast of Brittany where he established an artists' colony.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Russell had met Vincent van Gogh in Paris and formed a friendship with him.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Van Gogh spoke highly of Russell's work, and after his first summer in Arles in 1888 he sent twelve drawings of his paintings to Russell, to inform him about the progress of his work.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Monet often worked with Russell at Belle Île and influenced his style, though it has been said that Monet preferred some of Russell's Belle Île seascapes to his own.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Russell did not attempt to make his pictures known.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] In 1897 and 1898 Henri Matisse visited Belle Île.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Russell introduced him to impressionism and to the work of Van Gogh (who was relatively unknown at the time).
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] The island is the setting for portions of the novel *The Vicomte of Bragelonne: Ten Years Later*, Alexandre Dumas père's second sequel to *The Three Musketeers*.
[src:sea-trial/belle-ile] Dumas has his character Aramis fortify the island (in place of Vauban, historically) and Porthos dies there, in the caves of Locmaria.
[src:sea-trial/boat] A **boat** is a watercraft of a large range of types and sizes, but generally smaller than a ship, which is distinguished by its larger size or capacity, its shape, or its ability to carry boats.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Small boats are typically used on inland waterways such as rivers and lakes, or in protected coastal areas.
[src:sea-trial/boat] However, some boats (such as whaleboats) were intended for offshore use.
[src:sea-trial/boat] In modern naval terms, a boat is a vessel small enough to be carried aboard a ship.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Submarines are referred to as *boats* rather than *ships* regardless of their size.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Boats vary in proportions and construction methods according to their intended purpose, available materials, or local traditions.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Canoes have been used since prehistoric times and remain in use throughout the world for transportation, fishing, and sport.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Fishing boats vary widely in style, partly to match local conditions.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Pleasure craft used in recreational boating include ski boats, pontoon boats, and sailboats.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Houseboats may be used for vacationing or long-term residence.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Lighters are used to move cargo to and from large ships unable to get close to shore.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Lifeboats have rescue and safety functions.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Boats can be propelled by manpower (e.g., rowboats and paddle boats), wind (e.g., sailboats), and inboard/outboard motors (including gasoline, diesel, and electric).
[src:sea-trial/boat] The earliest watercraft are considered to have been rafts.
[src:sea-trial/boat] These would have been used for voyages such as the settlement of Australia, which occurred sometime between 50,000 and 60,000 years ago.
[src:sea-trial/boat] A boat differs from a raft by obtaining its buoyancy by having most of its structure exclude water with a waterproof layer, e.g., the planks of a wooden hull, the hide covering (or tarred canvas) of a currach.
[src:sea-trial/boat] In contrast, a raft is buoyant because it joins components that are themselves buoyant, such as logs, bamboo poles, bundles of reeds, and floats (such as inflated hides, sealed pottery containers, or, in a modern context, empty oil drums).
[src:sea-trial/boat] The key difference between a raft and a boat is that the former is a "flow through" structure, with waves able to pass up through it.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Consequently, except for short river crossings, a raft is not a practical means of transport in colder regions of the world, as the users would be at risk of hypothermia.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Today, that climatic limitation restricts rafts to between 40° north and 40° south, with similar boundaries in the past that have shifted as the world's climate has varied.
[src:sea-trial/boat] The earliest boats may have been either dugouts or hide boats.
[src:sea-trial/boat] The oldest recovered boat in the world, the Pesse canoe, found in the Netherlands, is a dugout made from the hollowed tree trunk of a *Pinus sylvestris* that was constructed somewhere between 8200 and 7600 BC.
[src:sea-trial/boat] This canoe is exhibited in the Drents Museum in Assen, Netherlands.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Other very old dugout boats have also been recovered.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Hide boats, made from covering a framework with animal skins, could be equally as old as logboats, but such a structure is much less likely to survive in an archaeological context.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Plank-built boats are considered, in most cases, to have developed from the logboat.
[src:sea-trial/boat] There are examples of logboats that have been expanded: by deforming the hull under heat, by raising the sides with added planks, or by splitting down the middle and adding a central plank to widen it.
[src:sea-trial/boat] (Some of these methods have been in quite recent use – there is no simple developmental sequence).
[src:sea-trial/boat] The earliest known plank-built boats are from the Nile, dating to the third millennium BC.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Outside Egypt, the next earliest are from England.
[src:sea-trial/boat] The Ferriby boats are dated to the early second millennium BC and the end of the third millennium BC.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Plank-built boats require a level of woodworking technology that was first available in the Neolithic with more complex versions only becoming achievable in the Bronze Age.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Boats can be categorized by their means of propulsion.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Powered by the crew-members on board, using oars, paddles or a punting pole or quant.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Towed – either by humans or animals from a river or canal bank (or in very shallow water, by walking on the sea or river bed) or by another vessel.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Powered by machinery, such as internal combustion engines, steam engines, or by batteries and an electric motor.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Any one vessel may use more than one of these methods at different times or in combination.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Several large vessels are usually referred to as boats.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Other types of large vessels which are traditionally called boats include Great Lakes freighters, riverboats, and ferryboats.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Though large enough to carry their own boats and heavy cargo, these vessels are designed for operation on inland or protected coastal waters.
[src:sea-trial/boat] The hull is the main, and in some cases only, structural component of a boat.
[src:sea-trial/boat] The keel is a boat's "backbone", a lengthwise structural member to which the perpendicular frames are fixed.
[src:sea-trial/boat] On some boats, a deck covers the hull, in part or whole.
[src:sea-trial/boat] While a ship often has several decks, a boat is unlikely to have more than one.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Above the deck are often lifelines connected to stanchions, bulwarks, perhaps topped by gunnels, or some combination of the two.
[src:sea-trial/boat] A cabin may protrude above the deck forward, aft, along the centerline, or cover much of the length of the boat.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Vertical structures dividing the internal spaces are known as bulkheads.
[src:sea-trial/boat] The forward end of a boat is called the bow, the aft end the stern.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Facing forward the right side is referred to as starboard and the left side as port.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Until the mid-19th century, most boats were made of natural materials, primarily wood, although bark and animal skins were also used.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Early boats include the birch bark canoe, the animal hide-covered kayak and coracle and the dugout canoe made from a single log.
[src:sea-trial/boat] By the mid-19th century, some boats had been built with iron or steel frames but still planked in wood.
[src:sea-trial/boat] In 1855, ferro-cement boat construction was patented by the French, who coined the name "ferciment".
[src:sea-trial/boat] This is a system by which a steel or iron wire framework is built in the shape of a boat's hull and covered over with cement.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Reinforced with bulkheads and other internal structures, it is strong but heavy, easily repaired, and, if sealed properly, will not leak or corrode.
[src:sea-trial/boat] As the forests of Britain and Europe continued to be over-harvested to supply the keels of larger wooden boats, and the Bessemer process (patented in 1855) reduced the cost of steel, steel ships and boats became more common.
[src:sea-trial/boat] By the 1930s, boats built entirely of steel, from frames to plating, were replacing wooden boats in many industrial uses and fishing fleets.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Private recreational steel boats remain uncommon.
[src:sea-trial/boat] In 1895, WH Mullins produced steel boats of galvanized iron, and by 1930, became the world's largest producer of pleasure boats.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Mullins also offered aluminium boats from 1895 through 1899 and once again in the 1920s, but it was not until the mid-20th century that aluminium gained widespread popularity.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Though much more expensive than steel, certain aluminum alloys do not corrode in salt water, allowing them to carry loads comparable to steel at much lower weight.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Around the mid-1960s, boats made of fiberglass (aka "glass fiber") became popular, especially for recreational boats.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Fiberglass is also known as "GRP" (glass-reinforced plastic) in the UK and "FRP" (fiber-reinforced plastic) in the US.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Fiberglass boats are strong and do not rust, corrode, or rot.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Instead, they are susceptible to structural degradation from sunlight and temperature extremes over their lifespan.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Fiberglass structures can be made stiffer with sandwich panels, where the fiberglass encloses a lightweight core such as balsa wood or foam.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Cold molding is a modern construction method that uses wood as the structural component.
[src:sea-trial/boat] In a single cold-molding process, very thin strips of wood are layered over a form.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Each layer is coated with resin, then another layer is laid on top at a 90-degree angle.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Subsequent layers may be stapled or otherwise mechanically fastened to the previous layer, or weighted or vacuum-bagged to provide compression and stabilization until the resin sets.
[src:sea-trial/boat] An alternative process uses thin plywood sheets shaped over a disposable male mold and coated with epoxy.
[src:sea-trial/boat] A boat displaces its weight in water, regardless of whether it is made of wood, steel, fiberglass, or even concrete.
[src:sea-trial/boat] If weight is added to the boat, the volume of the hull submerged below the waterline will increase to keep the weight above and below the surface balanced.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Boats have a natural or designed level of buoyancy.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Exceeding it will cause the boat first to ride lower in the water, second to take on water more readily than when properly loaded, and ultimately, if overloaded by any combination of structure, cargo, and water, sink.
[src:sea-trial/boat] As commercial vessels must be correctly loaded to be safe, and as the sea becomes less buoyant in brackish areas such as the Baltic, the Plimsoll line was introduced to prevent overloading.
[src:sea-trial/boat] Since 1998, all new leisure boats and barges built in Europe between 2.5m and 24m must comply with the EU's Recreational Craft Directive (RCD).
[src:sea-trial/boat] Europe is the main producer of recreational boats (the second-largest producer in the world is Poland).
[src:sea-trial/boat] European brands are known all over the world – in fact, these are the brands that created RCD and set the standard for shipyards around the world.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] A **cabin** or **berthing** is an enclosed space generally on a ship or an aircraft.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] A cabin which protrudes above the level of a ship's deck may be referred to as a **deckhouse**.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] In sailing ships, the officers and paying passengers would have an individual or shared cabin.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] The captain or commanding officer would occupy the "great cabin" that normally spanned the width of the stern and had large windows.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] On a warship, it was a privileged area, separate from the rest of the ship, for the exclusive use of the captain.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] In large warships, the cabin was subdivided into day and night cabins (bedrooms) by movable panels, called *bulk-heads*, that could be removed in time of battle to leave the cabin clear for the gunners to use the stern chasers several of which were usually stationed in the cabin.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] On large three decker warships in the Age of Sail the captain's cabin was sometimes appropriated by the Admiral.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] The captain would be consigned to the cabin below on the middle gun-deck.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] On smaller stations, where the flagship would sometimes be a frigate, the frigate would be modified by adding a cabin on the weather deck (poop deck) to serve as living space for a commodore or admiral.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] In most modern warships, the commanding officer has a main cabin—the **in-port cabin**, often adjacent to the ship's central control room (operations room)—and a **sea cabin** adjacent to the bridge.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] Thus, when likely to be called from sleep or attending to administration, the commanding officer can go to the sea cabin and thereby be able to appear at the bridge or operations room immediately.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] The sea cabin is sparsely equipped, containing just a bunk, a desk, and basic toilet facilities.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] The in-port cabin is more lavishly furnished, with separate bedroom and combination sitting room/office, and more elaborate toiletry facilities.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] For ships intended to act as flagships, like the former United States Navy aircraft carrier USS *Lexington*—now a museum ship—the admiral also has a sea cabin (adjacent to the captain's sea cabin) and an in-port cabin, in addition to the captain's cabins.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] Officers normally have their own cabins—sometimes referred to as **staterooms**—which double as their offices.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] Some senior petty officers may have cabins for similar reasons.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] In ships carrying passengers, they are normally accommodated in cabins, taking the terminology familiar to seafarers.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] First-class cabins were traditionally referred to as **staterooms**, and today many cruise lines now prefer to refer to passenger cabins as staterooms or suites.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] In cruise ship terms, a cabin crawl is an event where passengers tour the cabins of fellow passengers.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] A cruise ship may also offer a cabin crawl of cabins or suites which did not sell for a particular sailing.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] The purpose of a cabin crawl is to give passengers an idea of the space and layout of various cabin options for their next cruise.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] Cabin crawls are normally organized prior to a cruise, through cruise-fan websites.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] In spacecraft, cabins are required to fully supply food and oxygen for their crew.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] On missions lasting a year or longer, the cabins have to be self-sustaining, i.e. replenish their own water and oxygen.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] The space cabin for any long-range crewed mission is expected to be reasonably spacious, with approximately 28 cubic metres allotted to each occupant.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] In addition, cabins have life support systems that should have the capability to meet a variety of off-nominal conditions, including cabin fires, depressurization, and component shutdown or failure.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] Frequently, these conditions occur so quickly that recovery can be provided only by automatic control systems.
[src:sea-trial/cabin-ship] In the late 1960s, several experimental ground facilities were developed to evaluate regenerative life support systems for crewed space flight.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Ship launching imposes stresses on the ship not met during normal operation and in addition to the size and weight of the vessel represents a considerable engineering challenge as well as a public spectacle.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The process also involves many traditions intended to invite good luck, such as christening by breaking a sacrificial bottle of champagne over the bow as the ship is named aloud and launched.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] There are three principal methods of conveying a new ship from building site to water, only two of which are called "launching".
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The oldest, most familiar, and most widely used is the end-on launch, in which the vessel slides down an inclined slipway, usually stern first.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] With the side launch, the ship enters the water broadside.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] This method came into use in the 19th century on inland waters, rivers, and lakes, and was more widely adopted during World War II.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The third method is float-out, used for ships that are built in basins or dry docks and then floated by admitting water into the dock.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] If launched in a restrictive waterway, drag chains are used to slow the ship speed to prevent it striking the opposite bank.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Normally, ways are arranged perpendicular to the shore line (or as nearly so as the water and maximum length of vessel allows) and the ship is built with its stern facing the water.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Where the launch takes place into a narrow river, the building slips may be at a shallow angle rather than perpendicular, even though this requires a longer slipway when launching.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Modern slipways take the form of a reinforced concrete mat of sufficient strength to support the vessel, with two "barricades" that extend well below the water level taking into account tidal variations.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The barricades support the two launch ways.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The vessel is built upon temporary cribbing that is arranged to give access to the hull's outer bottom and to allow the launchways to be erected under the complete hull.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] When it is time to prepare for launching, a pair of standing ways is erected under the hull and out onto the barricades.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] (Tallow and whale oil were used as grease in sailing ship days.) A pair of sliding ways is placed on top, under the hull, and a launch cradle with bow and stern poppets is erected on these sliding ways.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The weight of the hull is then transferred from the build cribbing onto the launch cradle.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Provision is made to hold the vessel in place and then release it at the appropriate moment in the launching ceremony; common mechanisms include weak links designed to be cut at a signal and mechanical triggers controlled by a switch from the ceremonial platform.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] On launching, the vessel slides backwards down the slipway on the ways until it floats by itself.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Some slipways are built so that the vessel is side-on to the water and is launched sideways.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] This is done where the limitations of the water channel would not allow lengthwise launching, but occupies a much greater length of shore.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] *The Great Eastern* designed by Brunel was built this way, as were many landing craft during World War II.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] This method requires many more sets of ways to support the weight of the ship.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Sometimes ships are launched using a series of inflated tubes underneath the hull, which deflate to cause a downward slope into the water.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] This procedure has the advantages of requiring less permanent infrastructure, risk, and cost.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The airbags provide support to the hull of the ship and aid its launching motion into the water, thus this method is arguably safer than other options such as sideways launching.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] These airbags are usually cylindrical in shape with hemispherical heads at both ends.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] It is believed that ancient Egyptians, Greeks, and Romans called on their gods to protect seamen.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Favor was evoked from the monarch of the seas—Poseidon in Greek mythology, Neptune in Roman mythology.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Ship launching participants in ancient Greece wreathed their heads with olive branches, drank wine to honor the gods, and poured water on the new vessel as a symbol of blessing.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Shrines were carried on board Greek and Roman ships, and this practice extended into the Middle Ages.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The shrine was usually placed at the quarterdeck, an area which continues to have special ceremonial significance.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Different peoples and cultures shaped the religious ceremonies surrounding a ship launching.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Jews and Christians customarily used wine and water as they called upon God to safeguard them at sea.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Intercession of the saints and the blessing of the church were asked by Christians.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Ship launchings in the Ottoman Empire were accompanied by prayers to Allah, the sacrifice of sheep, and appropriate feasting.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The liturgical aspects of ship christenings, or baptisms, continued in Catholic countries, while the Reformation seems to have put a stop to them for a time in Protestant Europe.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] By the 17th century, for example, English launchings were secular affairs.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The christening party for the launch of the 64-gun ship of the line *Prince Royal* in 1610 included the Prince of Wales and famed naval constructor Phineas Pett, who was master shipwright at the Woolwich yard.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The "standing cup" was a large cup fashioned of precious metal.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] When the ship began to slide down the ways, the presiding official took a ceremonial sip of wine from the cup, and poured the rest on the deck or over the bow.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Usually the cup was thrown overboard and belonged to the lucky retriever.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] As navies grew larger and launchings more frequent, economy dictated that the costly cup be caught in a net for reuse at other launchings.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Late in 17th century Britain, the standing-cup ceremony was replaced by the practice of breaking a bottle across the bow.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Launching could be said to mark the birth of a vessel; and people throughout history have performed launching ceremonies, in part to appeal for good fortune and the safety of each new vessel.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] In Canada, Aboriginal peoples will perform ceremonies at the launching of vessels along with other methods of launching.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] French ship launchings and christenings in the 18th and early 19th centuries were accompanied by unique rites closely resembling marriage and baptismal ceremonies.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] A godfather for the new ship presented a godmother with a bouquet of flowers as both said the ship's name.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] No bottle was broken, but a priest pronounced the vessel's name and blessed it with holy water.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] In India, ships have historically been launched with a Puja ceremony that dedicates the ship to a Hindu god or goddess, and seeks blessings for her and her sailors.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Historically, Hindu priests would perform the *puja* ceremony at launch.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] In the 20th century, ships were launched with a lady breaking a coconut on the bow of the vessel, which is sometimes followed by a small Puja.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Japanese ship launchings incorporate silver axes which are thought to bring good luck and scare away evil.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Japanese shipbuilders traditionally order the crafting of a special axe for each new vessel; and after the launching ceremony, they present the axe to the vessel's owner as a commemorative gift.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The axe is used to cut the rope which tethers the ship to the place where she was built.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Sponsors of British warships were customarily members of the royal family, senior naval officers, or Admiralty officials.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] A few civilians were invited to sponsor Royal Navy ships during the nineteenth century, and women became sponsors for the first time.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] In 1875, a religious element was returned to naval christenings by Princess Alexandra, wife of the Prince of Wales, when she introduced an Anglican choral service in the launching ceremony for battleship *Alexandra*.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] In 1969, Queen Elizabeth II named the ocean liner *Queen Elizabeth 2* after herself, instead of the older liner RMS *Queen Elizabeth*, by saying, "I name this ship *Queen Elizabeth the Second*.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The Duchess of Rothesay similarly launched HMS *Prince of Wales* by pulling a lever which smashed a bottle of single malt Scotch whisky at the side of the ship.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] At the 2024 launching of CalMac ferry *Glen Rosa*, newly-qualified welder Beth Atkinson named the ship and pulled a lever to similarly smash a bottle, of single malt from the Ardgowan distillery at nearby Inverkip.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Shipyard ephemera is a rich source of detail concerning a launch and this was often material produced for the audience of the day and then thrown away.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Tyne & Wear Archives & Museums has many of these items from Tyne and Wear shipyards.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The 1900 piece for *Eidsvold* reproduced in this article lists a woman performing the launch.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Ceremonial practices for christening and launching ships in the United States have their roots in Europe.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] It was customary for the builders to celebrate a ship launching.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Rhode Island authorities were charged with overseeing construction of frigates *Warren* and *Providence*.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] No mention has come to light of christening a Continental Navy ship during the American Revolution.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The first ships of the Continental Navy were *Alfred*, *Cabot*, *Andrew Doria*, and *Columbus*.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] These were former merchantmen, and their names were assigned during conversion and outfitting.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Later, Congress authorized the construction of thirteen frigates, and no names were assigned until after four had launched.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The first description that we have of an American warship christening is that of *Constitution* at Boston, October 21, 1797, famous as "Old Ironsides." Her sponsor was Captain James Sever, USN, who stood on the weather deck at the bow.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] "At fifteen minutes after twelve she commenced a movement into the water with such steadiness, majesty and exactness as to fill every heart with sensations of joy and delight." As *Constitution* ran out, Captain Sever broke a bottle of fine old Madeira over the heel of the bowsprit.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] As the 19th century progressed, American ship launchings continued to be festive occasions, but with no set ritual except that the sponsor(s) used some "christening fluid" as the ship received her name.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Sloop of war *Concord* was launched in 1828 and was "christened by a young lady of Portsmouth." This is the first known instance of a woman sponsoring a United States Navy vessel.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The contemporaneous account does not name her.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The first *identified* woman sponsor was Lavinia Fanning Watson, daughter of a prominent Philadelphian.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] She broke a bottle of wine and water over the bow of sloop-of-war *Germantown* at Philadelphia Navy Yard on August 22, 1846.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Women as sponsors became increasingly the rule, but not universally so.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] As sloop-of-war *Plymouth* "glided along the inclined plane" in 1846, "two young sailors, one stationed at each side of her head, anointed her with bottles, and named her as she left her cradle for the deep." As late as 1898, the torpedo boat *MacKenzie* was christened by the son of the builder.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Wine is the traditional christening fluid, although numerous other liquids have been used.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] *Princeton* and *Raritan* were sent on their way in 1843 with whisky.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Seven years later, "a bottle of best brandy was broken over the bow of steam sloop *San Jacinto*." Steam frigate *Merrimack* earned her place in naval history as Confederate States of America ironclad *Virginia*, and she was baptized with water from the Merrimack River.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Admiral David Farragut's famous American Civil War flagship steam sloop *Hartford* was christened by three sponsors; two young ladies broke bottles of Connecticut River water and Hartford, Connecticut spring water, while a naval lieutenant completed the ceremony with a bottle of sea water.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Champagne came into popular use as a christening fluid as the 19th century closed.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] A granddaughter of Secretary of the Navy Benjamin F.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Tracy wet the bow of *Maine*, the Navy's first steel battleship, with champagne at the New York Navy Yard on November 18, 1890.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The effects of national prohibition on alcoholic beverages were reflected to some extent in ship christenings.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Cruisers *Pensacola* and *Houston*, for example, were christened with water; the submarine *V-6* with cider.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] However, battleship *California* appropriately received her name with California wine in 1919.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Champagne returned in 1922, but only for the launch of light cruiser *Trenton*.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Rigid naval airships *Los Angeles*, *Shenandoah*, *Akron*, and *Macon* were built during the 1920s and early 1930s, carried on the Naval Vessel Register, and each was formally commissioned.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The earliest First Lady of the United States to act as sponsor was Grace Coolidge who christened the airship *Los Angeles*.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Lou Henry Hoover christened *Akron* in 1931, but the customary bottle was not used.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Instead, the First Lady pulled a cord which opened a hatch in the airship's towering nose to release a flock of pigeons.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] Thousands of ships of every description came off the ways during World War II, the concerted effort of a mobilized American industry.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] The historic christening and launching ceremonies continued, but travel restrictions, other wartime considerations, and sheer numbers dictated that such occasions be less elaborate than those in the years before the war.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] On 15 December 1941, the United States Maritime Commission announced that as a war-time measure all formal launching ceremonies would be discontinued for merchant ships being constructed under its authority, though simple informal ceremonies could continue without reimbursement to builders.
[src:sea-trial/ceremonial-ship-launching] In addition to the ceremonial breaking of a champagne bottle on the bow, the sponsor remains in contact with the ship's crew and is involved in special events such as homecomings.
[src:sea-trial/certification] As a rule, certificates must be renewed and periodically reviewed by a certifying regulatory body responsible for the validity of the certificate's assessment methods.
[src:sea-trial/certification] The certifying body can be either a state authority or an independent private company.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Certificates may even be issued by the companies themselves that use them, primarily as a marketing gimmick, which can be characterized as "cheap talk," meaning a trick that does not guarantee trust.
[src:sea-trial/certification] A study conducted by the Certification Board of Computing Professionals (CBCP) showed that the average salary increase for IT professionals who obtained CompTIA certificates was 15%.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Similarly, a study by the Project Management Institute (PMI) found that certified PMP® project managers earn on average 20% more than their non-certified counterparts.
[src:sea-trial/certification] One of the most common types of certification in modern society is professional certification, where a person is certified as being able to competently complete a job or task, usually by the passing of an examination and/or the completion of a program of study.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Some professional certifications also require that one obtain work experience in a related field before the certification can be awarded.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Some professional certifications are valid for a lifetime upon completing all certification requirements.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Others expire after a certain period of time and have to be maintained with further education and/or testing.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Certifications can differ within a profession by the level or specific area of expertise to which they refer.
[src:sea-trial/certification] For example, in the IT Industry there are different certifications available for software tester, project manager, and developer.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Also, the Joint Commission on Allied Health Personnel in Ophthalmology offers three certifications in the same profession, but with increasing complexity.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Certification does not designate that a person has sufficient knowledge in a subject area, only that they passed the test.
[src:sea-trial/certification] This of course apples only to exam-based certifications.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Education-based certifications, require that a person completes a course of study that satisfies certain body of knowledge claims to demonstrate that the person has sufficient knowledge in the subject area.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Certification does not refer to the state of legally being able to practice or work in a profession.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Usually, licensure is administered by a governmental entity for public protection purposes and a professional association administers certification.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Licensure and certification are similar in that they both require the demonstration of a certain level of knowledge or ability.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Another common type of certification in modern society is product certification.
[src:sea-trial/certification] This refers to processes intended to determine if a product meets minimum standards, similar to quality assurance.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Different certification systems exist in each country.
[src:sea-trial/certification] For example, in Russia it is the GOST R Rostest.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Certification is dependent on meeting specific requirements that are defined in a technical standard.
[src:sea-trial/certification] This is either an international standard or a private standard.
[src:sea-trial/certification] ISEAL Alliance and Global Food Safety Initiative are examples of private organizations who represent the private sector.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Promoting certification in supply chains of private corporations by recognizing scheme owners who adopt private standards.
[src:sea-trial/certification] In comparison, the public sector and Intergovernmental organizations (IGOs) recommend international standards.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Scheme owners using private standards require scheme fees, which is typically an annual payment for issuing a certificate.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Whereas international standards do not allow scheme ownership and do not require fees to issue a certificate.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Further differences between international standards and private standards are explained in a paper from ISO.
[src:sea-trial/certification] In the European Union, a notified Body is an organization accredited by an accreditation body for the purpose of providing third-party certification and testing services of the standards and regulations within the purview of the accreditation body.
[src:sea-trial/certification] This serves to enforce regulatory compliance with these codes, and gives providers of goods and services a means of demonstrating compliance by way of an official certification mark or a declaration of conformity.
[src:sea-trial/certification] For software testing, the certifications can be grouped into exam-based and education-based.
[src:sea-trial/certification] For exam-based certifications the candidate must pass an exam, which can also be learned by self-study.
[src:sea-trial/certification] For example, for International Software Testing Qualifications Board Certified Tester by the International Software Testing Qualifications Board or Certified Software Tester by QAI or Certified Software Quality Engineer by American Society for Quality.
[src:sea-trial/certification] Education-based certifications are the instructor-led sessions, where each course has to be passed.
[src:sea-trial/certification] The Certified Software Test Professional (CSTP), the Certified Agile Software Test Professional (CASTP), the Certified Test Manager (CTM) and other certifications by Institute for Software Testing are such examples.
[src:sea-trial/certification] It is common for people who require certifications to undergo paid structured learning to help them achieve their goals.
[src:sea-trial/certification] In certification systems based on participation, certification is developed by a network of participants, such as groups of producers and consumers.
[src:sea-trial/certification] These systems are based on trust and networks for sharing knowledge and experience.
[src:sea-trial/certification] In such cases, we refer to them as participatory guarantee systems.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The **Compagnie Générale Transatlantique** (**CGT**, and commonly named "**Transat**"), typically known overseas as the **French Line**, was a French shipping company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Established in 1855 by the brothers Émile and Issac Pereire under the name *Compagnie Générale Maritime*, the company was entrusted by the French government to transport mail to North America.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1861, the name of the company was changed to *Compagnie Générale Transatlantique*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company's first ship, SS *Washington*, had its maiden voyage on 15 June 1864.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] After a period of trial and error in the late 19th century, the company, under the direction of its presidents Jules Charles-Roux and John Dal Piaz, gained fame in the 1910s and 1930s with its famous ocean liners such as SS *Paris*, SS *Île de France*, and especially SS *Normandie*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Weakened by World War II, the company regained its fame in 1962 with the famous SS *France*, but the ship suffered major competition from air transport and was retired from service in 1974.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1977, the company merged with the Compagnie des Messageries Maritimes to form the Compagnie Générale Maritime (CGM).
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Then, in 1996, the company and the Compagnie Maritime d'Affrètement (CMA) merged to form the CMA CGM.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Contrary to what its name suggests, the company did not operate only on the North Atlantic route.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It also offered service to Central America and even, for a time, the Pacific coast.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] From the beginning of the 20th century, it offered crossings between Marseille and Algiers, creating a tourist circuit in North Africa in the 1920s.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In the 1930s, the company briefly became involved in aviation through Air France Translatlantique.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Other than operating ocean liners, the company also had a significant fleet of cargo ships.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The cargo service was started in the 1900s.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The ocean liners of CGT were often symbolic works of art of their time; they were intended to represent an image of France abroad.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The quality of services aboard, such as that of meals and wines, had attracted wealthy clientele, including Americans at the time of the Prohibition in the United States.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Years after the company's demise, its heritage continues to attract collectors and is showcased in exhibitions.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1855, the Pereire brothers, Émile and Isaac, founded the Compagnie Générale Maritime in Granville, Manche.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Already owners of many railway companies, they were a part of a current of French industrialists who founded large companies under the leadership of Napoleon III.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In the 1850s, there was a strong need for a French merchant fleet.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The Pereires were also at the head of a credit organization, Société Générale de Crédit Mobilier, which became the main shareholder of the new company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The Compagnie Générale Maritime was thus officially founded on February 24, 1855, and Adolphe d'Eichthal became its first president until 1861.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company was founded upon the takeover of the “Terreneuvienne”, a cod fishing company founded two years previously which owned many sailboats.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The first years of the company were disorganized: the shipping routes multiplied in an anarchic way, using up a great part of the company's initial capital.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] After this near-bankruptcy, the Pereires understood that, like the Cunard Line, they would be better off focusing on an ocean liner service financed by postal agreements.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Napoleon III, seduced by the concept, proposed a number of agreements at the time, which the Pereires refused, judging them to be too weak.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The route to the Americas was thus given to Louis Victor Marziou instead, but he was unable to develop it due to a lack of investors in 1860.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was at this moment that Isaac Pereire chose to renegotiate an agreement with the French government.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In return, the government would provide the company with an annual subsidy.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1861, an imperial decree changed the company's name to Compagnie Générale Transatlantique, to better correspond to its new roles.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] To meet the contractual requirement that its fleet be built in France, the company must find local shipyards.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] With the construction of its first six ships having begun abroad (in particular SS *Washington*, the first liner built for the New York route), the Péreires were well aware of the prices charged by foreign shipyards.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, the prices offered by the domestic La Seyne-sur-Mer shipyards were significantly higher.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Thus they acquired land near Saint-Nazaire and founded the Chantiers et Ateliers de Saint-Nazaire (later better known as the Chantiers de Penhoët).
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Engineers from the Scottish shipyards of John Scott came to provide their expertise to French workers and architects.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the time, the shipyards only built the hulls of their ships; the engines inside those ships were purchased from Le Creusot.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1862, two years ahead of schedule, SS *Louisiane* inaugurated the route to Mexico, becoming the company's first success.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This route's creation was particularly anticipated by the government because of the second French intervention in Mexico.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Two years later, service on the New York – Le Havre route began with the paddle-steamer SS *Washington* providing postal service.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was later joined by SS *France* (first of this name) and SS *Impératrice Eugénie*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1867, the company switched from using paddle wheels to using propellers for its ships, partly because they were more fuel efficient.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Taking advantage, among other things, of the American Civil War and the weakening of the American fleet, the company succeeded in conquering new markets.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The Pereires notably set up a service specifically intended for French emigrants.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] An economic and financial crisis in 1868 forced the Pereire brothers to file a petition of bankruptcy and to resign from the company's board.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The Franco-Prussian War of 1870 and the uncertain beginnings of the French Third Republic further reduced the traffic and profits of the transatlantic route while competition from other shipping companies increased.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1873, as the company was recovering, its first major accident occurred.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] SS *Ville du Havre* collided with the sailing ship *Loch Earn*, with a loss of life of about 226 people.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company's situation seemed catastrophic.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1875, the Pereires brothers were called back to take over the company's helm again in order to ensure its recovery.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] So it was Isaac and his son Eugène who led the recovery.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In particular, they extended their activity by taking advantage of the virtual absence of competition to open a service in the Mediterranean between Marseille and Algiers in 1879.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In that same year, the company became public.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the beginning of the 1880s, the need arose to build new, more modern ships.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The first, ordered under the name *Ville de New York*, was put into service under the name of *Normandie* then quickly renamed *La Normandie*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] With its 145 meters length and its 6,500 gross tonnage, it was the first liner of the company to be equipped with electric lighting and promenade decks.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the same time, the company had to renew the postal agreement of 1861, before its expiration in 1885.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The commission responsible for it renewed it in 1883, on the condition that the company quickly obtained four more liners capable of speed greater than 15 knots.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This was already the case for *La Normandie*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The four new ships were SS *La Champagne*, SS *La Bourgogne*, SS *La Gascogne*, and SS *La Bretagne*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] They were assigned to the New York route in 1886, while a large percentage of the company's older ships were reassigned to the Central America route.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Despite this major renewal, the company's fleet was facing increasing competition from foreign shipping companies.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The success of these four ships was immediate, however, and revenue almost doubled in four years.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The quality of life aboard these liners was also important and contributed to the increased fame of the company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] With the White Star Line having just put into service its fast RMS *Teutonic*, and the Inman Line with its SS *City of New York*, the company felt the need to respond.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This prompted the construction of SS *La Touraine* in 1891.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Slightly larger, and, above all, faster than its predecessors (19 knots on average), it however remained below the performance of its competitors (it narrowly failed to conquer the Blue Riband).
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Nevertheless, it was built at the right time to allow the replacement of the boilers of SS *La Normandie*, and especially to take advantage of the World Columbian Exposition to be held in the United States in 1893.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1894, it was also used for luxury cruise service in the Mediterranean, notably to Istanbul.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The late 1890s were particularly unfavorable for the company for a number of reasons.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The Spanish–American War, an economic crisis, and changes in customs legislation, as well as an epidemic of cholera in France partially reduced the passenger traffic, while new, increasingly imposing ocean liners were emerging abroad, such as SS *Kaiser Wilhelm der Grosse* and RMS *Oceanic*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Added to this were several maritime disasters, notably the abandonment at sea of SS *City of Saint-Nazaire* (1897) and the disappearance of the cargo ship *Pauillac* which was later revealed to have been purchased at a low price from another company and was in poor condition.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Worse still for the company was the sinking of its SS *La Bourgogne* in 1898, which claimed 568 lives.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The biggest disaster known to the company, it made a strong impression on public opinion, which quickly judged that the company was responsible for the tragedy.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the same time, the company was struggling to renovate its fleet.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the end of the 19th century, SS *La Touraine*, flagship of the fleet, was clearly outdated.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The necessary renewal of the postal convention, for adapting to the new demands of the market, hardly came and was only carried out at the turn of the years 1897/1898.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was only then that the building of new ships SS *La Lorraine* and SS *La Savoie* could begin; they entered service in 1900 and 1901 respectively.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Although much larger than *La Touraine*, with 170 meters and 11,000 tons, they still struggled to compete by their size with ships such as RMS *Celtic*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] A final growing problem was that of President Eugène Pereire, who had become blind and deaf, and considered increasingly senile.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] He was finally ousted in 1904 and the board of directors was overhauled.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was the end of the reign of the Pereire family over the company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1904, Jules Charles-Roux became president and instituted a reorganization of the company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] His leadership led to a new strategy of winning back customers who had turned away from the company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Charles-Roux took advantage of several trips to the United States to meet with many wealthy industrialists and gain their customer loyalty to the company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In the same vein, he decided on a change of policy by targeting a new clientele.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The race for speed seemed to be an increasingly irrelevant idea as the prices of coal made high speeds unprofitable.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Charles-Roux and most engineers, who agreed with him on this point, considered that the speed of liners had reached a plateau which can only be exceeded by technological change.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The White Star Line had, moreover, made the same observation a few years earlier by putting into service its "Big Four".
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The last projects of the former leadership came to fruition in these years, in particular the liner SS *La Provence*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The third ship built according to the postal agreement of the end of the nineteenth century, it is significantly larger than its predecessors (190 meters, 13,000 tons).
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company gradually acquired wealthy customers, while innovations were also installed.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] *La Provence* was the company's first liner to be equipped with wireless telegraphy.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This allowed passengers to communicate with the mainland, but above all to receive news from the world while aboard.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] An onboard daily newspaper, *L'Atlantique*, was created for passengers.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the same time, the company further developed its cargo service by putting into service a fleet of increasingly large freighters, on the route to North Africa, but also that of New York and from Central America.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The weight of goods transported by the company tripled between 1903 and 1913.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company also increased its transportation of emigrants.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Although France was not, in itself, a land of emigration, the company benefited from the increase in migrants.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1907, it came in fifth in terms of the number of migrants transported to the United States, and second place in the reverse direction.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1912, the company put into service a new liner, SS *France*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Even though it remained clearly below its competitors in terms of size, it posted an average speed of 24 knots which was very appreciable at the time, and was 210 meters in length.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Its luxury earned it the nickname "the Versailles of the Atlantic," and the ship quickly gained the loyalty of a wealthy clientele.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] To appeal to less wealthy passengers, the company also launched new ships such as SS *Chicago* in 1908 and SS *Rochambeau* in 1911.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Smaller and slower, these liners cost less to the company, which mainly operated them for migrants, to whom they often offered services superior to the larger liners of the time.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This strategy quickly proved effective, and this type of vessels quickly established itself alongside larger, faster liners which formed the flagship of the fleet.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In the summer of 1913, a new postal agreement was reached, requiring the construction of three new liners before 1932.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The building of the first, SS *Paris*, was immediately started in Penhoët.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was designed to be bigger than its predecessor.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The ship was expected to be completed in 1916, but World War I greatly delayed its completion.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This decade under the governance of Charles-Roux was on the whole particularly prosperous: the revenues from the main routes almost doubled between 1905 and 1913.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, the operating costs also increased, with the number of ships no fewer than 84 ships.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Its results remain comparable to those of its competitors, and the CGT has established itself as a leading French company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1910, coal burners in Le Havre went on strike.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In response, the company posted inflammatory posters on the quays, mobilized the anti-strike "yellow" union, and demanded that the police protect the freedom to work.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Incidents multiplied: confrontation with the police, nighttime sabotage, fights between strikers and non-strikers, etc.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] On September 10, Louis Dongé, a member of the "yellow" union, was killed in a fight with drunkards.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Local company officials seized on this the opportunity to neutralize the strike.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Jules Durand, secretary of Le Havre charcoal union, was accused by false witnesses, bought by the company, of having had his union voted for the assassination of Louis Dongé.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The strike he had been leading for three weeks then came to an abrupt end.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Conservative newspapers (*Le Temps*, *L'Aurore*, *Le Capitaliste*, etc.) denounced the "return to barbarism" and demanded energetic measures against the trade unionists.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The government declared itself ready to resort to illegal measures against insurrectional strikes.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the end of the trial, Jules Durand was sentenced to death.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The whole Left mobilized, from the socialist Jean Jaurès to the anarchist Sébastien Faure, including the trade unionist Georges Yvetot and Paul Meunier.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Across France, crowds marched against "class injustice" and hundreds of public meetings were organized.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Internationally (Italy, United Kingdom, United States, Australia, etc.) strikes and rallies were carried out in support of Durand.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Under pressure, President Armand Fallières commuted the sentence to seven years' imprisonment.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The mobilizations did not weaken, and Durand was released on February 16, 1911.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, he went insane in his captivity.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Traumatized by his detention and sentencing, he experienced delusion of persecution, no longer recognized his relatives and banged his head against the walls.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] He was placed in a mental asylum until the end of his life in April 1926, and his innocence was officially recognized in 1918.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] When World War I broke out in August 1914, company's activity was abruptly halted.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Instructions were given to ships moored in ports to remain there until further notice.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, customer pressure was high, with many Americans keen to leave Europe.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company finally made the decision to allow, at its own risk, two crossings for this purpose, using SS *Chicago* and SS *France*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, the cessation of activity remained fairly brief.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The French government insisted that the postal service be maintained.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] After a massive wave of departures for the United States, the number of passengers dropped dramatically.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] *France* was taken off service, while smaller ships such as SS *Espagne* (originally assigned to Central America route), SS *Chicago*, SS *Rochambeau* and older ships such as SS *La Touraine* replaced it on the New York route.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The greatest involvement of the company in the war, however, was in the area of military operations.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Thirty-seven ships (two-fifths of the fleet) were requisitioned.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Following the example of the British and Germans, the company designated a number of its large liners to serve as auxiliary cruisers.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This was the case for SS *La Provence*, SS *La Savoie*, SS *La Lorraine* and SS *La Touraine*, which were requisitioned at the start of the war to ensure the blockade of Germany.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The last two were however quickly returned to postal service.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] As the conflict spread to the Middle East, the fleet's presence in the Mediterranean became necessary.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Several ships such as SS *Charles-Roux* and SS *France* were transformed into hospital ships in order to collect the wounded.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The latter was also used to bring troops from the United States.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Finally, the liners and freighters that continued their commercial service brought back to Europe many goods necessary for the war effort.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The war resulted in a large number of losses for the company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Submarine warfare, in particular, took a heavy toll.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company struggled to replace them with hastily purchased freighters to continue supporting the war effort.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The surviving ships were, for their part, in poor condition.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The biggest loss was that of SS *La Provence*, the second largest ship of the company, which sank in 1916 with more than 1000 victims.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] As soon as the war ended, a vast and costly reconstruction program had to be launched.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] A new era dawned for the company, a feeling reinforced by the death of Jules Charles-Roux in 1918.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] After a two-year interlude provided by Gaston de Pellerin de Latouche, who himself died in 1920, the presidency was taken over by John Dal Piaz, who had already enjoyed a brilliant career within the company under Eugène Péreire.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Following the war, the company's priority was to rebuild its fleet.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It acquired a few ships (three small liners and three freighters) as a result of war reparations, but they never brought in any profit.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The building of SS *Paris* was finished in 1921 to provide the company with a new flagship.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Several ships were built between 1921 and 1924, including SS *Cuba*, bound for Central America, and SS *De Grasse*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] A substantial number of freighters were also built in this decade, bringing the number of ships in the fleet to a hundred at the end of the 1920s.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] After the war, the flagships of the company, in particular *Paris*, benefited from an influx of migrants from Central Europe, while winning the loyalty of a wealthy clientele.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1927, *Île de France* was completed and put into service.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was a liner slightly larger than *Paris*, but more up to date.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The first class occupied a greater place on the ship, while the class reserved for immigrants was drastically reduced in size.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The particularly luxurious liner attracted the public, who nicknamed it "Rue de la Paix de l'Atlantique." John Dal Piaz also provided the North African route with liners like SS *Lamoricière*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In order to diversify the company's activity, Dal Piaz created the Société des Voyages et Hôtels Nord Africains in 1925 in order to offer tourist motor car circuits to customers.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The system reached its peak in the late 1920s.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company experienced a success and massively increased its clientele by taking advantage of the Prohibition in the United States, which pushed American passengers to travel on French liners in order to consume alcoholic beverages.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In June 1928, John Dal Piaz died after a short illness.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company selected the industrialist André Homberg to succeed him.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Shortly before his death, Dal Piaz had laid the foundations for a project to rejuvenate the fleet.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] On the transatlantic route, this involved replacing SS *France* and SS *Rochambeau*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] For the latter, SS *Champlain* and SS *Lafayette*, both medium-sized ships, were ordered and expected to be completed in 1932.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] SS *Colombia* was put into service on the Central America route.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In addition, many freighters were built.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Finally, studies were made to design a new ship for the New York route, then named "super *Île-de-France*" or "T6." Loans were made to cover these numerous expenses.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] These projects were launched when the Great Depression began.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company's revenues plummeted, its expenses increased, and the it found itself on the verge of bankruptcy.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This forced it to appeal to the government, in particular to renegotiate its postal agreement.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Indeed, the T6 could no longer be completed in 1932 as previously agreed.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The government agreed to assist the company, on the condition that it became a semi-public company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company was for a time placed in the hands of Raoul Dautry, before being handed over to two men chosen by the government: Governor General Marcel Olivier, who was appointed as president, and Henri Cangardel who became its Administrator and Chief Executive Officer.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] A consolidation of finances was undertaken.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The oldest liners, like SS *France*, were sold for scraps, and others like SS *Paris* were assigned to cruise service in the off-season.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The postal agreement was renegotiated in a way more favorable to the company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the same time, the building of *T6*, which in the meantime became *Normandie*, was controversial.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] There were those who believed that the money could be better spent elsewhere.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, the investment already made was such that the company would lose a lot if the work was stopped before completion.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] When the ship was completed in 1935, Cangardel, Olivier, as well as the engineer Jean Marie, engaged in a difficult media exercise with a lot of conferences to extol the merits of the ship.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Commanded by Captain Pierre-Louis Thoreux, the liner made a speed record and won the Blue Riband on its inaugural crossing.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] For the first time, France possessed the largest liner ever built, and also the fastest.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The acquired prestige managed to satisfy the press; the company got back on its feet; and the controversy subsided.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The following year, significant competition began against the Cunard Line and its liner RMS *Queen Mary*, it and *Normandie* having similar level of performances.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company thus found itself on the front of the competition, directly against a foremost shipping company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] With the start of World War II in 1939, the company was called upon to participate in the war effort.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] For safety, large liners like SS *Normandie* and SS *Île-de-France* were moored in the port of New York.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Then the conflict became a war of attrition, but the traffic resumed normally for most of the minor ships of the company, despite Germany's maritime operations, particularly those underwater.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, the Fall of France in June 1940 was all the more painful for the company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The new regime quickly reorganized the management of the company, removing Jean Marie (president since 1939) in favor of Henri Cangardel.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The war had already damaged the company's fleet.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Moreover, with the war having interrupted all traffic on the Atlantic, the majority of the activity of the company was relocated to the North African route.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, not all ships fell to the Vichy regime.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Remaining in New York, the *Normandie* was under close surveillance by the American authorities who feared a possible sabotage.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Following the attack on Pearl Harbor, the US government requisitioned the ship to support the war effort.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It accidentally caught fire and capsized during its conversion into a troopship in February 1942.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The largest ship in of the company was thus found to be unusable after only four years of commercial service.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The *Île-de-France* and several other ships benefited from the resistant fiber of company's General Staff, which managed to make them sail on behalf of the forces of Free France and the United Kingdom.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In the war, the liner transported 300,000 soldiers, both in the Atlantic and in the Indian Ocean.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] After France was liberated, Henri Cangardel was again replaced by Jean Marie.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Of the large liners, only the *Île-de-France* survived (the *Paris* caught fire shortly before the conflict), and it had to undergo a major refit after its war service.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In all, the company lost 13 liners and 40 freighters, representing 60% of each of the two categories.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The *Île-de-France* being under restoration, and the other large ships of the company having been sunk, the company could not restore its transatlantic service immediately.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It therefore recovered ships that can be recovered, starting with SS *De Grasse*, which was put back into service in 1947.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In order to replace the loss of the *Normandie*, the United States ceded to the company a liner taken from Germany, SS *Europa*, which was renamed SS *Liberté*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The *Liberté* was taken to the port of Le Havre for refitting, but it collided with the wreck of *Paris* during a storm, causing it to be half-sunk.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was raised and towed to the Ateliers et Chantiers de Saint-Nazaire Penhoët shipyard in Saint-Nazaire to complete its refitting.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In order to replace the large number of cargo ships lost in the war, the company received a total of thirty-two liberty ships.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The French government also funded the building of some freighters.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] For the reconstruction of France and its ports, the CGT transported many tons of freight.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The transport of goods became its main activity during this period.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] On April 14, 1947, the company fell victim to another disaster.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The cargo of ammonium nitrate on *Grandcamp*, one of its Liberty ships, detonated in the Texas City disaster, killing at least 581 people in the deadliest industrial disaster of that period.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1950, the company acquired the Compagnie générale transsaharienne, which operated land and air transport across the Sahara.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In the area of passenger traffic, recovery was gradual.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At first slow at the end of the 1940s, it grew stronger the following decade.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1952, SS *Liberté* and SS *Île-de-France* carried more passengers than the number that the five largest ships in the fleet had carried in 1938.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The Antilles routes and North African route, despite the growing importance of air transport, managed to benefit from a stable customer base.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The management of the company, especially its president Jean Marie, remained however convinced that aircraft and ocean liner were called upon to serve complementary roles: the aircraft providing a fast transport, and the ocean line providing a voyage that was comfortable for more passengers.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The figures seemed, at first, to prove him right.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The number of passengers was increasing, and the share of the aircraft remained moderate.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, the fleet of the company was by then old, and of fewer number than that of foreign companies.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This made it difficult to compete, in particular, with RMS *Queen Mary* and RMS *Queen Elizabeth* of the Cunard Line, or with new liners such as SS *United States* or SS *Andrea Doria*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Faced against them, the company responded only with SS *Flandre*, a smaller liner intended to replace *De Grasse*, and with SS *Antilles*, which was assigned to the Central American route.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Gradually the profits decreased as the ships aged.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The building of a new large-scale liner was therefore envisaged by Jean Marie.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1959, after thirty-two years of service and despite great popularity, the *Île-de-France* was scrapped.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The *Liberté* reached its 30th birthday in 1960.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] For Jean Marie, it was essential to give the company a new ship to proudly wear its flag while ensuring that it carried the number of passengers that previously required two to three ships to carry.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This was the birth of the liner SS *France* which was launched in 1960 in the presence of President Charles De Gaulle, and then put into service in 1962.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The ship was intended to be large and fast.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, the company made the mistake of devoting 80% of its capacity to the tourist class while air transport gains 80% of those traveling crossing the Atlantic, and less wealthy passengers quickly preferred air travel.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the same time, the company underwent major changes in its leadership.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Jean Marie, whose retirement was scheduled for 1961, must be replaced.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Its managing director, Edmond Lanier, was expected to take over, but it was the president of Messageries Maritimes, Gustave Anduze-Faris, who took up the post, before himself retiring in 1963.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] He was replaced by Pierre Renaud, who left in 1964.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Lanier then became president and stayed in the position for nearly ten years.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] For several years now, the company had been mostly operating freighters.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, for President Lanier, the defense of SS *France* as a symbol of the company was essential, while the ship's operational deficits widened from the mid-1960s onward.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Various solutions were considered but the regular transatlantic route was losing profits, and the ships which crossed it became more and more rare.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Several cruises were organized, including the "imperial" cruise for celebrating the bicentennial of the birth of Napoleon I and the around-the-world cruises in 1972 and 1974.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, the ship, built for the cold climate of the North Atlantic, was not designed for tropical heat, and full-time operation of it as a cruise ship proved costly.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Following the 1973 oil crisis, the operation of SS *France* became even less profitable.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In February 1974, the French government waived the compensatory subsidy which allowed the liner to continue to sail.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Edmond Lanier, its main advocate, retired in September 1973, and died in October of the following year.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the same time, in September 1974, when the *France* finished its last crossing at Le Havre, the crew mutinied.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The ship was finally decommissioned at the end of October.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The last liner of the Compagnie Générale Transatlantique stopped sailing.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company was living its last hours as a passenger ship business.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Since the middle of the 1950s, it has devoted an increasingly important part of its activity to freight traffic.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1976, the company merged with the Compagnie des Messageries Maritimes de Marseille to form the Compagnie Générale Maritime.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The CGM operated as a container ship business.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1996, CGM merged with Compagnie Maritime d’Affrément, becoming CMA CGM, one of the world's largest container shipping companies.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The main route served by the Compagnie Générale Transatlantique is the Le Havre – New York route, inaugurated in 1864 and operated almost continuously until 1974.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was on this route that the most advantageous postal agreements were negotiated, that the passengers were the most numerous, and the liners the most prestigious.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company's flagships, from SS *La Champagne* to SS *Normandie* to SS *France*, were built for this route, which brought in more than half of the revenues of the company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This did not prevent the liners from taking part, in the off-season, in cruises, such as the Mediterranean cruises of SS *La Provence*, the around-the world cruise of the *France*, or the cruise of the *Normandie* to Rio de Janeiro.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The demand for routes to Central America and the West Indies were also heavily exploited.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The route to Mexico was the first, opened by the company in 1862.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Several aged liners were, once replaced on the New York route, assigned near the end of their career to this route.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, several large ships of the company, such as the *Cuba*, the *Columbie*, and *Antilles*, also served on it.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This route also gradually became very popular, especially after World War II, with the company's freighters, which brought back to France large quantities of rum, sugar and bananas.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1879, the company obtained agreements for the operation of a route off-center in relation to its main activities, that which connected Marseille to Algiers.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Requiring different ships designed for short crossings, it quickly became prosperous, and several ships were assigned to it, such as *Ville d'Alger* which, in the 1930s, won the speed record on this route, and SS *Lamoricière*, which sank on this route.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Gradually a traffic of goods was also set up on this route, in particular cereals, fruits and wines, which compensated for the losses caused by the competition of the aircraft for the passenger traffic.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company has also served Corsica since July 6, 1880, using the liner *Ville de Madrid* on the route Marseille – Ajaccio – Bône – Algiers.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1882, the company inaugurated routes entirely dedicated to Corsica extending to Sardinia from Marseille and Nice.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Although the activities of the Compagnie Générale Transatlantique had always been centered around the oceans, the company could not ignore the technological progress in the area of civil aviation made at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This new tool quickly appeared to be very valuable in the company's postal activities.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Thus, in 1928, John Dal Piaz had a seaplane catapult installed on SS *Île-de-France*, which enabled mails to be delivered to their recipients one day before the ship's arrival at its destination.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The arrival of Henri Cangardel in the management sphere of the company, in 1933, accentuated this gaze towards the sky.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Cangardel had, in fact, been commissioned a few years earlier to participate in the study of the Compagnie générale aéropostale.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] He thus became friends with great pilots like Jean Mermoz and Antoine de Saint-Exupéry.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1933, the company Air France was created, but the problem concerning the transatlantic route, for which no connection by plane was yet possible, remained.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was within this framework that Air France Transatlantique, in which the CGT had a large share, was created in 1937, in order to bring its experience regarding routes.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] As the airline studied the various possible routes, the shipping company shared its expertise in the field of meteorology, continuing its studies using the ship *Carimaré*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] From 1937 to 1939, Air France Transatlantique made twelve seaplane flights between France and the United States via the Azores, as well as the first flight between New York and Biscarrosse without stopover.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The war subsequently hampered the development of the airline, and representatives of the CGT were excluded from the airline after 1945, before its merger with Air France.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Despite this setback, however, the CGT was no stranger to air traffic.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Even though its leaders underestimated the competition from aircraft on the transatlantic route, they were perfectly aware of its power on the Mediterranean route, and of the impact it has on the route Marseille – Algiers.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Many companies were flourishing on the route, frightening both Air France and the CGT.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The latter, under the impetus of Edmond Lanier], who was in charge of aviation issues, then decided to provide financial support to the Compagnie Air Transport, being eager to get involved in the aviation industry once again.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The CGT also contributed to the creation of Compagnie des Transports Aériens – Air Algérie, and established a majority stake in it.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The airline seemed promising, but Algeria gaining its independence ended the CGT's stake in the airline in 1962.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] From its inception, the CGT gradually adopted new technological innovations.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This was particularly the case with propulsion.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] *Washington*, when it entered service in 1864, was propelled by paddle wheels.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1868, it was refitted to become the first liner to be propelled by twin propellers, which allowed for higher speeds.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At that time, passengers still showed some suspicion towards steam propulsion, however, and until the 1890s all of the company's ships were fitted with masts capable of carrying sails.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Thus, the first express liners of the company, SS *La Normandie* and SS *La Champagne*, traveled using both sails and steam.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The last liner of the company to travel using both these at the same time was SS *La Touraine*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was then considered from that point on that multiple propellers were sufficient precaution in the event of engine failure.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The masts were not abandoned, however, since they served as a support for the lookout nests, lighting, and later, the telegraph cables.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] SS *Rochambeau* of 1911 was CGT's first ship to be propelled by a combination of reciprocating steam engines and exhaust steam turbines.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This configuration was intended to achieve higher fuel efficiency than either reciprocating engines or steam turbines alone, and to be more flexible at low speeds than a ship propelled by direct-drive turbines.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] SS *France* of 1912 was propelled purely by steam turbines, which allowed it to reach high speeds and to be one of the fastest ships of its time, behind RMS *Lusitania* and RMS *Mauretania*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1935, SS *Normandie* marked the peak of these technological innovations.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It had a hydrodynamic hull designed by the architects of the Chantiers de Penhoët with the help of Vladimir Yourkevich.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Added to this was a turbo-electric propulsion considered to be more reliable and economical for a ship of this size.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company also kept pace with innovations affecting passenger comfort.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1882, SS *La Normandie* was the first ship of the company to be equipped with electric light, replacing the dangerous kerosene lamps.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] SS *La Provence* was the first ship of the company to be equipped with wireless telegraphy (six years after SS *Kaiser Wilhelm der Grosse*, the first liner to be equipped with this technology).
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This technology was, at the time, seen as a gadget intended for wealthy passengers, and not as a security tool.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In particular, it made it possible to publish an onboard newspaper communicating news from the outside world.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Finally, the company innovated little by little in the field of safety at sea.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] SS *France* of 1912 was the first large liner of the company to be equipped with enough lifeboats for all its passengers, only one week after the sinking of RMS *Titanic*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1935, the *Normandie* was for its part particularly secure from danger of onboard fire, which affected several large ships and became the main danger at sea.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The safety of passengers during the crossing was also ensured, with a gradual improvement of the onboard medical area.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1965, SS *France* became the first liner to transmit by satellite the electrocardiogram results of one of its passengers, allowing a surgery to be conducted at sea in collaboration with European and American teams.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The CGT, being far away from major migratory routes, and restricted in the development of its ships by the size of the port of Le Havre, was not really able to benefit from the financial windfall from emigrants, as the German and British companies did.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company therefore specialized in wealthy passengers, who quickly became its main market.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] At the beginning of the 19th century, the company's liners thus developed a reputation for being sumptuous ships, where the French art of living — especially gastronomy and wine — reigned supreme.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] SS *France* of 1912 was the first to truly benefit from this reputation.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Its particularly sumptuous decoration (even loaded, compared to its British rivals), was inspired by great works of French architecture: castles, mansions, etc.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In addition, there were copies of famous works of art, which gave to the ship the nickname "Versailles of the Atlantic." This level of decoration had already been successful on SS *La Provence*, SS *La Savoie*, and SS *La Lorraine*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In the 1920s, on SS *Paris* the style evolved.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The Art Deco style began to appear, without completely replacing the decorations of the Belle Époque.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The number of services offered to passengers — such as movies and dance events — were increasing.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The ship underwent a major refit in 1929, following a fire, which allowed its style to be updated.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] SS *Île-de-France* stood out much more; it was designed as a ship to represent the architecture of its time.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Great French architects and decorators are thus invited to fill the spaces of the ship, which were larger than usual.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Moreover, the long career of the ship allowed it to carry multiple different styles.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Once again, the facilities offered on board were multiple: panoramic café, boxing ring, chapel, etc.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] With SS *Normandie*, the same perspective was pursued on a much wider scale.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] As the ship was of enormous proportions, it was equipped with a monumental dining room occupying three of its decks.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] There were luxury suites and works of art typical of 1930s French art were displayed throughout the ship.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] With *Normandie*, the aim was also to promote French etiquette abroad.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] After World War II, when the time came to refit SS *Île-de-France* and to rebuild SS *Liberté*, certain decorative elements of *Normandie* were used to give a more familiar atmosphere to the two ships, which were refitted to adopt the styles of the early 1950s.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] SS *France* of 1962 featured the very colorful fittings of the 1960s, once again appealing to the famous artists of that period.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] This time, however, the company changed its policy.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It, which until then favored the first class, now devoted more than three quarters of its facilities to the tourist class.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The history of Compagnie Générale Transatlantique was marked by several major maritime disasters.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1873, the liner SS *Ville du Havre*, which had just entered service after a major refit, twice collided with other ships.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] On June 6, it collided with and sank a sailboat in the Hudson River, but escaped without serious damage.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] On November 22, it collided with the iron clipper *Loch Earn* and sank in about ten minutes with the loss of 226 lives; only 61 passengers and 26 crew members survived.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] On March 6, 1897, SS *Ville de Saint-Nazaire* experienced a major hull leak and had to be abandoned.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Out of 83 people aboard, only 18 survived.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The deadliest event was the sinking of SS *La Bourgogne* in 1898, following a collision with a sailing ship.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Only 13% of the passengers survived while 48% of the crew did; this contrast in casualties resulted in a scandal that weakened the position of Eugène Péreire within the company.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In the 1930s, the French shipping industry was affected by the fire on and the sinking of MS *Georges Philippar* of the Messageries Maritimes on its maiden voyage and by the 1933 fire aboard SS *L'Atlantique* of the Compagnie de Navigation Sud Atlantique, a subsidiary of the CGT.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1938, SS *Lafayette*, a barely eight-year-old liner, caught fire in the port of Le Havre.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The ship was rendered unusable and sent for scrapping.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1929, SS *Paris* caught fire while docked at Le Havre and was severely damaged, but was successfully repaired and returned to service.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] However, ten years later in 1939, it caught fire again at Le Havre; this time the water used to put out the fire caused it to capsize; the wreck remained there until after World War II.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In 1946, The newly acquired SS *Liberté* was being refitted at Le Havre when a heavy gale blew it into the wreck of *Paris*, causing *Liberté* to run aground.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It was refloated, repaired, and put into service.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The wreck of *Paris*, meanwhile, was scrapped on site in 1947.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The most famous fire that affected the company was that of the *Normandie*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] It had been seized by the U.S. and was under conversion into a troopship in February 1942 when welding set it on fire.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The inexperience of American sailors recently assigned to the liner effectively rendered the numerous fire protection devices aboard ineffective.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The water poured into it caused it to capsize.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company lost many ships in the two World Wars.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] Thirty of the company's ships were sunk in World War I, the first of which was SS *La Provence*, which was sunk by torpedo with the loss of about a thousand lives.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] In World War II, the company lost 53 ships.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] They included 13 liners, with SS *Champlain* (lost to a mine) and SS *De Grasse* (which was refloated and returned to service after the war) among them.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p01] The company also lost SS *Lamoricière* in the war due to a storm en route between Algiers and Marseille in 1942, killing nearly 300 people and leaving 90 survivors.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] In its 120 years of existence, the Compagnie Générale Transatlantique has acquired a special place within the French shipping industry, and a particular prestige with foreign customers, especially Americans.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] Its large liners, especially SS *Normandie* and SS *France*, have been the subject of numerous works.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] The company benefited from a special aura, in particular thanks to the celebrities who have traveled aboard its ships.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] Traveling aboard also inspired artists: it was after a trip aboard SS *Flandre* (then renamed *Carla C*) that a passenger wrote a book titled *Love Boats*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] The French film *Paris-New York* was filmed aboard *Normandie* in 1939, with Michel Simon and Gaby Morlay as star actors.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] SS *France* of 1962 served as the setting for the final scene of the French film *The Brain* with Bourvil and Jean-Paul Belmondo, as well as for *Gendarme in New York*, with Louis de Funès.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] The company's ships also gained a certain amount of affection from the public.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] The accidental end of *Normandie* aroused indignation; it remained stifled by the scale of the war that reigned at the time.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] This did not prevent the emergence of persistent rumors about sabotage as the cause of the fire.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] The scrapping of SS *Île-de-France* in 1959 caused its share of protests; the liner had, in its career, acquired great affection from the public as a result of its exemplary service in the conflict, as well its rescue of the survivors of the sinking of SS *Andrea Doria*.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] The decommission of SS *France* in 1974, also created strong emotion: Michel Sardou dedicated a song, titled *Le France*, to it to express his anger.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] Once the ship was returned to service under the name SS *Norway* for Norwegian Cruise Line, it aroused great enthusiasm each time it returned to France, where the French press and the French public continued to regard it as the *France* until it was scrapped at the end of the 2000s.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] Some relics of the cargo ship *Wisconsin*, built for CGT in 1929, are preserved in Szczecin, Poland.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] The ship was sold to Poland in 1951 and was scrapped in 1985.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] Its mast was erected as a monument and a part of its superstructure has also been preserved.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] Finally, the company's legacy survives through the collectibles carried by passengers, and sold at auction: postcards published by the Company at the beginning of the 20th century, representing the ships painted by Ernest Lessieux, luggage tags, dishes, menus, etc.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] Since 1995, the French Lines Association, created on the initiative of the Compagnie Générale Maritime, has kept the archives and objects once owned by the CGT, and ensures the enhancement of this heritage, in particular through exhibitions and sales of those objects.
[src:sea-trial/compagnie-générale-transatlantique-p02] Other future projects continue to highlight the heritage of the company, such as the planned building of a new ship named *France* by Didier Spade.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] A **sea trial** or **trial trip** is the testing phase of a watercraft (including boats, ships, and submarines).
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] It is also referred to as a "shakedown cruise" by many naval personnel.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] It is usually the last phase of construction and takes place on open water, and it can last from a few hours to many days.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] Sea trials are conducted to measure a vessel's performance and general seaworthiness.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] Testing of a vessel's speed, maneuverability, equipment and safety features are usually conducted.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] Usually in attendance are technical representatives from the builder (and from builders of major systems), governing and certification officials, and representatives of the owners.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] Successful sea trials subsequently lead to a vessel's certification for commissioning and acceptance by its owner.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] Although sea trials are commonly thought to be conducted only on new-built vessels (referred by shipbuilders as 'builders trials'), they are regularly conducted on commissioned vessels as well.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] In new vessels, they are used to determine conformance to construction specifications.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] On commissioned vessels, they are generally used to confirm the impact of any modifications.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] Sea trials can also refer to a short test trip undertaken by a prospective buyer of a new or used vessel as one determining factor in whether to purchase the vessel.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] Sea trials are fairly standardized using technical bulletins published by ITTC, SNAME, BMT, regulatory agencies or the owners.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] They involve demonstrations and tests of the ship's systems and performance.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] In a speed trial the vessel is ballasted or loaded to a predetermined draft and the propulsion machinery is set to the contracted maximum service setting, usually some percentage of the machinery's maximum continuous rating (ex: 90% MCR).
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] The ship's heading is adjusted to have the wind and tide as close to bow-on as possible.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] The vessel is allowed to come to speed and the speed is continuously recorded using differential GPS.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] The trial will be executed with different speeds including service (design) and maximum speed.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] The ship is then turned through 180° and the procedure is followed again.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] This reduces the impact of wind and tide.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] The final "Trials Speed" is determined by averaging all of the measured speeds during each of the runs.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] This process may be repeated in various sea states.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] To test a crash stop, the vessel is ballasted or loaded to a predetermined draft and the propulsion machinery is set to the contracted maximum service setting, usually some percentage of the machinery's maximum continuous rating.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] The trial begins once the order to "Execute Crash Stop" is given.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] At this point the propulsion machinery is set to full-astern and the helm is put hard-over to either port or starboard.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] The speed, position and heading are continuously recorded using differential GPS.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] The final time to stop (i.e.: ship speed is 0 knots) track line, drift (distance traveled perpendicular to the original course) and advance (distance traveled along the original course line) are all calculated.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] The trial may be repeated at various starting speeds.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] During endurance trials the vessel is ballasted or loaded to a predetermined draft and the propulsion machinery is set to the contracted maximum service setting, usually some percentage of the machinery's maximum continuous rating.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] The fuel flow, exhaust and cooling water temperatures and ship's speed are all recorded.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] Maneuvering trials involve a number of trials to determine the maneuverability and directional stability of the ship may be conducted.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] These include a direct and reverse spiral manoeuvres, zig-zag, and lateral thruster use.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] Seakeeping trials were originally used exclusively for passenger ships, but are now used in a variety of vessels.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] They involve measurements of ship motions in various sea states, followed by a series of analyses to determine comfort levels, likelihood of sea sickness and hull damage.
[src:sea-trial/sea-trial] Trials are usually protracted in nature due to the unpredictability of finding the correct sea state, and the need to conduct the trials at various headings and speeds.
